<DOC><DOCNO> ZF310-625-546 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 625 546.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Information Week  April 15 1991 n316 p44(5).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Are you getting what you're worth? Despite the recession, salariesfor top IS executives continue to rise. (Cover Story)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Krass, Peter.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Salaries for top information systems (IS) executives are on therise and are outpacing inflation.andP;  Median base salary of 116executives polled has risen over 9 percent from $129,000 in 1990to $142,000 in 1991.andP;  Pay for IS chiefs is ahead of the averagecompensation earned by heads of other functions in the samecompanies.andP;  In another survey conducted by Hay ManagementConsultants in Philadelphia, PA, IS executives earned an averagetotal compensation (salary plus benefits) of almost $147,000.andP;  Insome corporations, however, IS is considered overhead andadministrative expense, and is often the target of cost-cuttinginitiatives by senior executives.andP;  The size of an IS executive'spaycheck could depend on the view top management has of IS ingeneral.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Management of EDPMISSalaryExecutiveSurveyManagement/EDP RelationsEmployee Benefits.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraph.andO;Caption:   IS salaries by industry. (graph)Beyond salary... other kinds of IS compensation. (graph)IS salaries by years in the profession. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>